[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426398&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426398&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Alright, now that the DDN sites have been considered, how about
those of us without direct TCP connections?  Hosts behind gateways,
like on CSNET for example, should be able to send mail out without
much real trouble by just sending any mail to particular domains
through our gateway.

What looks to be more difficult is nickname resolution.  Right now
ARPAnet host tables are available which contain the nicknames, so
code can look up a given host specification and be sure it really
exists before sending the mail off to the gateway.  This is a nice
feature in that it catches all the mistyped host names while the user
is still logged on.

Any ideas on how this can be accomplished once the DDN no longer
needs hosts.txt?  It would be reasonable to say that not all hosts
need be listed, as the user can be given a message and then asked
whether to proceed, and up-to-the-minute information isn't needed.
But the most common host nicknames should certainly be provided, and
something better than a manually updated list maintained separately
by each site would be nice.

- Dave

